editAgentRounds.reply: I'll update the project's `web.xml` files to use the Jakarta namespace (compatible with Tomcat 11) so deployments won't fail due to descriptor/schema mismatch; then I'll run the workspace error checker. I'll change the root `<web-app>` declaration in each project's `WEB-INF/web.xml` to the Jakarta namespace and a modern servlet version.

I'll update the four old web.xml files that use the java.sun.com namespace to the Jakarta namespace/version compatible with Tomcat 11 (change only the web-app header). After the edits I'll check for errors.

You're getting that error because your web application descriptors are using the old Java EE (javax / java.sun.com) web-app namespace while your Tomcat is Tomcat 11 (Jakarta EE); Tomcat 11 expects the Jakarta EE namespace (jakarta.* and the https://jakarta.ee XML namespace). I'll explain what I changed and how to fully fix and verify the deployment.

What I'll do next (done)
- Quick plan: inspect servlet sources and web.xml files, detect namespace mismatch, update old web.xml headers to Jakarta namespace, re-check for errors.
- Action taken: I updated the web-app root element in these files to the Jakarta EE namespace / version (compatible with Tomcat 11):
  - `JokeCalculator/src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/web.xml`
  - `MyCalc/src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/web.xml`
  - `MyWeatherApp/src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/web.xml`
  - `MyWebCalculator/src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/web.xml`
- I also inspected servlets and the server config; servlet sources are already using jakarta.servlet imports (which is correct for Tomcat 11).

Root cause (short)
- Tomcat 11 and Jakarta EE 9+ moved the Java EE package names from javax.* to jakarta.* and changed the XML namespaces for descriptors.
- If your `WEB-INF/web.xml` uses the old `http://java.sun.com/xml/ns/j2ee` / `version="2.x"` descriptor, Tomcat 11 will fail to parse/deploy it (you typically see errors like "SEVERE: Failed to parse deployment descriptor" or "java.lang.ClassNotFoundException: javax.servlet.http.HttpServlet" depending on which mismatch occurs).
- Conversely, if your code or libraries were compiled against the old javax.* APIs, they will fail on Tomcat 11.

What I changed
- Replaced the old web-app header (java.sun.com) with Jakarta EE header and version 5.0 for the four web.xml files shown above. The rest of each descriptor (welcome files, display-name) was left unchanged.

Other possible causes you should check
1. Compiled classes referencing javax.*:
   - If the .class files were compiled against javax.servlet (Servlet API before Jakarta), they will reference javax.servlet.* and fail at runtime on Tomcat 11 (ClassNotFoundException). Solution: recompile your projects against jakarta.servlet-api (5.x/6.x) or recompile in your IDE configured to use the Jakarta servlet API.
2. Servlet API jar inside WEB-INF/lib:
   - Do not ship the servlet API (jakarta or javax servlet JAR) inside your WAR's WEB-INF/lib. The container provides it. Having the wrong one can cause classloading conflicts.
3. Third-party libraries (JARs) that still use javax.*:
   - Some older libraries (or JDBC drivers bundled with code using javax servlet classes as servlets/filters) will not work. Either update them to Jakarta-aware versions or use a bytecode migration (Eclipse Transformer) to rewrite packages.
4. web.xml version vs schema:
   - My edits set the descriptor to Jakarta namespace and version 5.0. Tomcat 11 accepts Jakarta descriptors (it ships web.xml defaults in jakarta namespace). If you need a different version, align schemaLocation and version accordingly.

How you can verify / quick tests
- Restart Tomcat and watch the logs for deployment errors. On Windows (cmd.exe), you can check logs under Tomcat's logs folder (or your server adapter logs). Example commands to tail or view the latest log (adjust path to your Tomcat installation):
  - (Open the log file in Notepad or type it)
  ```
  type "C:\path\to\tomcat\logs\catalina.<date>.log"
  ```
  - Or to run curl against the servlet (assuming Tomcat is started and the app name and mapping):
  ```
  curl http://localhost:8080/JokeCalculator/MyServlet
  ```
  Expected response: the string from your doGet (e.g., "Do get is calling").

Recommended full fix checklist
- [ ] Ensure all `WEB-INF/web.xml` files use Jakarta namespace (done for the four I updated).
- [ ] Rebuild/recompile all projects against Jakarta Servlet API (jakarta.servlet-api 5.x/6.x). If you use Maven/Gradle, set the servlet API dependency to provided scope and target jakarta packages.
- [ ] Remove any servlet-api jars from `WEB-INF/lib`.
- [ ] Replace or migrate any third-party libs that still reference javax.* (update to Jakarta-compatible versions or use a migration tool).
- [ ] Redeploy and check Tomcat logs for remaining errors.

Common error messages you may have seen (and what they mean)
- "SEVERE: PWC3998: Error parsing deployment descriptor" — descriptor uses wrong namespace/schema.
- "java.lang.ClassNotFoundException: javax.servlet.http.HttpServlet" — classes depend on javax servlet API but Tomcat provides jakarta servlet API.
- "javax.servlet.ServletException: Container unable to find a resource" — mapping/descriptor mismatch or descriptor failed to deploy.

Status and next steps from me
- I updated the web.xml descriptors listed and ran a quick workspace error check — no immediate static errors reported.
- If you still see the original error when deploying, paste the exact Tomcat log lines (SEVERE / stacktrace) here and I will:
  - Diagnose the exact remaining incompatibility (class not found vs descriptor parse vs third-party),
  - Suggest exact commands to recompile or transform artifacts,
  - Or perform more edits in the repo if you want (e.g., add a jakarta servlet API dependency, adjust build scripts).

If you want, I can:
- Recompile the projects for you (if you tell me how you build them: Ant, Maven, or manual javac),
- Scan the jars in `WEB-INF/lib` for references to `javax.servlet` vs `jakarta.servlet` and report any problem jars,
- Or convert any class files that still reference javax.* using an automated transformer.

Tell me which of those you'd like me to do next, or paste the exact Tomcat error/log you saw and I’ll diagnose that specific message.
